04173nam a22005535i 9780520937536DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20052005cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209375367 a10.1525/97805209375362doi  a(DE-B1597)520059  a(OCoLC)1086458914  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aHQ691.7b.P65 2005eb 7aHIS0260002bisacsh04a306.85/09622221 aPollard, Lisa, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNurturing the Nation :bThe Family Politics of Modernizing, Colonizing, and Liberating Egypt, 1805-1923 /cLisa Pollard. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2005] 4cÂ©2005  a1 online resource (302 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote On Translation And Transliteration -- tIntroduction -- t1. My House And Yours: Egyptian State Servants And The New Geography Of Nationalism -- t2. Inside Egypt: The Harem, The Hovel, And The Western Construction Of An Egyptian National Landscape -- t3. Domesticating Egypt: The Gendered Politics Of The British Occupation -- t4. The Home, The Classroom, And The Cultivation Of Egyptian Nationalism -- t5. Table Talk: The Home Economics Of Nationhood -- t6. Reform On Display: The Family Politics Of The 1919 Revolution -- tConclusion: It'S A Girl! Gender And The Birth Of Modern Egyptian Nationalism -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFocusing on gender and the family, this erudite and innovative history reconsiders the origins of Egyptian nationalism and the revolution of 1919 by linking social changes in class and household structure to the politics of engagement with British colonial rule. Lisa Pollard deftly argues that the Egyptian state's modernizing projects in the nineteenth century reinforced ideals of monogamy and bourgeois domesticity among Egypt's elite classes and connected those ideals with political and economic success. At the same time, the British used domestic and personal practices such as polygamy, the harem, and the veiling of women to claim that the ruling classes had become corrupt and therefore to legitimize an open-ended tenure for themselves in Egypt. To rid themselves of British rule, bourgeois Egyptian nationalists constructed a familial-political culture that trained new generations of nationalists and used them to demonstrate to the British that it was time for the occupation to end. That culture was put to use in the 1919 Egyptian revolution, in which the reformed, bourgeois family was exhibited as the standard for "modern" Egypt.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aFamiliesxEgypt. 0aFamilieszEgypt. 0aFamily policyxCross-cultural studiesxHistoryxEgypt. 0aFamily policyzEgyptvCross-cultural studiesxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520937536423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520937536.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles